it may sit in your fridge for a few more
days before being eaten over this period
of potentially weeks the food may lose
up to 50% of its nutritional value
Frozen Foods on the other hand are
picked when they're ripe and Frozen
immediately and while the quick freeze
process does affect some of the vitamin
content it essentially freezes or locks
most of the nutrients in place next to
the fresh produce that has been sitting
around for weeks there's no doubt that
frozen foods can contain more nutrition
particularly during the months that
local produce is not in season and
traveling far distances in a series of
studies after 3 days of storage frozen
broccoli had higher levels of vitamin C
and beta keratine frozen blueberries
were much higher in polyphenols and
anthocyanins and Frozen Sprouts scored
higher on all nutrient measurements of
course if you pick a fresh vegetable
from your garden or get it from a local
farmers market and eat it that day

Frozen produce can be a great
